ef>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   \n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" /> \n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "lockdown summarized for lede", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "FC Schalke 04", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Schalke 04\n| upright = .8\n| fullname = Fu\u00dfballclub Gelsenkirchen-Schalke 04 e.V.\n| current = 2019\u201320 FC Schalke 04 season\n| image = FC Schalke 04 Logo.svg\n| alt = crest\n| nickname = ''Die K\u00f6nigsblauen'' (The Royal Blues)<br/>''Die Knappen'' (The Miners)\n| short name = S04\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1904|5|4}}\n| ground = [[Arena AufSchalke|Veltins-Arena]], [[Gelsenkirchen]]\n| capacity = 62,271<ref name=\"Stadionkapazit\u00e4t\" />\n| owntitle = President\n| owner = [[:de:Clemens T\u00f6nnies|Clemens T\u00f6nnies]]<ref name=\"Supervisory Board\">{{Cite web |url=https://schalke04.de/en/club/fc-schalke-04/offices-and-councils/supervisory-board/ |title=Supervisory Board |website=FC Schalke 04}}</ref>\n| chrtitle = Executive Board\n| chairman = [[:de:Alexander Jobst|Alexander Jobst]]<ref name=\"Managing Board\">{{Cite web |url=https://schalke04.de/en/club/fc-schalke-04/offices-and-councils/managing-board/ |title=Managing Board |website=FC Schalke 04}}</ref><br />[[Peter Peters (football official)|Peter Peters]]<ref name=\"Managing Board\" /><br />[[:de:Jochen Schneider (Fu\u00dfballfunktion\u00e4r)|Jochen Schneider]]<ref name=\"Managing Board\" />\n| manager = [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]]\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| league = [[Bundesliga]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]\n| position = 14th\n| website = http://www.schalke04.de\n| pattern_la1 = _schalke1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _schalke1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _schalke1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _schalke1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _schalke1920h\n| leftarm1 = 0E00F7\n| body1 = 0E00F7\n| rightarm1 = 0E00F7\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = 0E00F7\n| pattern_la2 = _schalke1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _schalke1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _schalke1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = _schalke1920a\n| pattern_so2 = _schalke1920a\n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = 0000AA\n| socks2 = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3 = _schalke1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = \n| pattern_sh3 = _schalke1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _schalke1920t\n| leftarm3 = 000000\n| body3 = 000000\n| rightarm3 = 000000\n| shorts3 = 000000\n| socks3 = 000000\n}}\n{{Schalke 04 sections}}\n'''Fu\u00dfballclub Gelsenkirchen-Schalke 04 e. V.''', commonly known as '''FC Schalke 04''' ({{IPA-de|\u025bf tse\u02d0 \u02c8\u0283alk\u0259 n\u028al fi\u02d0\u0250\u032f|lang}}), '''Schalke''', '''Schalke 04''' or abbreviated as '''S04''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u025bs n\u028al fi\u02d0\u0250\u032f|lang}}), is a [[Professionalism in association football|professional]] [[Football in Germany|German football]] and multi-[[sports club]] originally from the [[:de:Gelsenkirchen-Schalke|Schalke]] district of [[Gelsenkirchen]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. The \"04\" in the club's name derives from its formation in 1904. Schalke has long been one of the most popular professional [[football team]]s and multi-sports club in Germany, even though the club's heyday was in the 1930s and 1940s. Schalke play in the [[Bundesliga]], the top tier of the [[German football league system]]. As of June 2018, the club has 155,000 members, making it the second-largest sports club in Germany<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2018-19/fc-schalke-04-2/vereinsinformationen.html |title=fc schalke |date=11 November 2018 |access-date=11 November 2018}}</ref> and the fourth-largest sports club in the world in terms of membership.{{citation needed lead|date=August 2018}} Other activities offered by the club include [[sport of athletics|athletics]], [[basketball]], [[team handball|handball]], [[table tennis]], [[winter sport]]s and [[eSports]].\n\nFounded in 1904, Schalke has won seven [[List of German football champions|German championships]], five [[DFB-Pokal]]s, one [[DFL-Supercup]] and one [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]].\nSchalke also succeeded as the first German club to win a cup double in 1937.\n\nSince 2001, Schalke's stadium has been the [[Arena AufSchalke|Veltins-Arena]]. Schalke holds a long-standing rivalry with [[Ruhr]] neighbours [[Borussia Dortmund]], arguably one of the most widespread and well-known rivalries in German football, and matches between the two teams are referred to as the [[Revierderby]].\n\nSchalke was ranked as the 31st-best football team in Europe by [[UEFA]]'s 2020 [[UEFA coefficient#UEFA Team Ranking|UEFA club rankings]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl/bert/uefa/data/method5/trank2020.html |title=UEFA Team Ranking 2020 |publisher=kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl |access-date=2 March 2020}}</ref> and ranked 7th-best in 2015 [[UEFA coefficient#Club coefficient|UEFA club rankings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl/bert/uefa/data/method4/trank2015.html |title=UEFA Team Ranking 2015 |publisher=kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl |access-date=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of [[operating income]], Schalke possesses the seventh-highest [[operating income]] of any football club at [[United States dollar|$]]64.4&nbsp;million or [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]38.2&nbsp;million ([[Euro|\u20ac]]48&nbsp;million),<ref name=\"Forbes List\" /> and 0 per cent [[debt]] as of August 2014.<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\" /> Schalke also generates the 14th-highest [[revenue]] of any football club, at \"$265.6&nbsp;million or \u00a3157.8&nbsp;million (\u20ac198&nbsp;million)\".<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\" />\n\nIn May 2014, Schalke 04 were ranked by ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine as the [[Forbes' list of the most valuable football clubs|14th-most valuable football club]],<ref name=\"Forbes List\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/soccer-valuations/list/ |title=Soccer Team Values |date=May 2014 |website=Forbes |access-date=1 August 2014}}</ref> at \"\u00a3355&nbsp;million or $599&nbsp;million (\u20ac446&nbsp;million)\", an increase of 16% from the previous year.<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/schalke-04/ |title=Schalke 04 |date=May 2014 |website=Forbes |access-date=1 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Schalke's early years===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F015017-0006, Gelsenkirchen-Buer, Kohlebergbau.jpg|thumb|1900s typical mining structure in the Ruhr, source of the Schalke nickname Die Knappen \u2013 from an old German word for \"miners\"\u2013 because the team drew so many of its players and supporters from the coalmine workers of Gelsenkirchen.]]\nThe club was founded on 4 May 1904 as '''Westfalia Schalke''' by a group of high school students and first wore the colours red and yellow. The team was unable to gain admittance to the ''Westdeutscher Spielverband'' and played in one of the \"wild associations\" of early German football. In 1912, after years of failed attempts to join the official league, they merged with the gymnastic club '''Schalker Turnverein 1877''' in order to facilitate their entry. This arrangement held up until 1915, when '''SV Westfalia Schalke''' was re-established as an independent club. The separation proved short-lived and the two came together again in 1919 as '''Turn- und Sportverein Schalke 1877'''. The new club won its first honours in 1923 as champions of the ''Schalke Kreisliga''. It was around this time that Schalke picked up the nickname ''Die Knappen'', from an old German word for \"miners\" because the team drew so many of its players and supporters from the coal miners of Gelsenkirchen.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn 1924, the football team parted ways with the gymnasts again, this time taking the club chairman along with them. They took the name '''FC Schalke 04''' and adopted the now familiar blue and white [[Kit (association football)|kit]] from which their second nickname would derive, ''Die K\u00f6nigsblauen'' ({{lang-en|The Royal Blues}}). The following year, the club became the dominant local side, based on a style of play that used short, sharp, man-to-man passing to move the ball. This system would later become famous as the ''Schalker Kreisel'' ({{lang-en|spinning top; gyroscope}}). In 1927, it carried them into the top-flight ''Gauliga Ruhr'', onto the league championship, and then into the opening rounds of the national finals. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n===Rise to dominance===\nThe popular club built a new stadium, the Gl\u00fcckauf-Kampfbahn, in 1928, and acknowledged the city's support by renaming themselves '''FC Gelsenkirchen-Schalke 04'''. They won their first West German championship in 1929, but the following year were sanctioned for exceeding salary levels set by the league and, in an era that considered professionalism in sport to be anathema, found themselves banned from play for nearly half a year.\n\nHowever, the ban had little impact on the team's popularity: in their first match after the ban against [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]], in June 1931, the team drew 70,000 spectators to its home ground. The club's fortunes begun to rise from 1931 and they made a semi-final appearance in the [[1932 German football championship|1932 German championship]], losing 1\u20132 to [[Eintracht Frankfurt]]. [[1933 German football championship|The year after]], the club went all the way to the final, where Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf proved the better side, winning 3\u20130.<ref>''kicker Almanach 1990'' {{in lang|de}}, publisher [[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]], published: 1989, page: 171</ref>\n\nWith the re-organisation of German football in 1933 under [[Nazi Germany]], Schalke found themselves in the [[Gauliga Westfalen]], 1 of 16 top-flight divisions established to replace the innumerable regional and local leagues, all claiming top status. This league saw Schalke's most successful decade in their history: from 1933 to 1942, the club would appear in 14 of 18 national finals (ten in the German championship and eight in the [[Tschammerpokal#Tschammer-Pokal|Tschammerpokal]], the predecessor of today's [[DFB-Pokal]]) and win their league in every one of its eleven seasons.\n\nThe club never lost a home match in the Gauliga Westfalen in all these 11 seasons and only lost six away matches, while remaining unbeaten in the 1935\u201336, 1936\u201337, 1937\u201338, 1938\u201339, 1940\u201341 and 1942\u201343 seasons, a sign of the club's dominance.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Die deutschen Gauligen 1933\u201345 \u2013 Heft 1\u20133 |language=de |publisher=[[DSFS]]}}</ref>\n\n===The championship years (1934\u201342)===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-2004-1001-503, Berlin, Zuschauer beim Fu\u00dfball-Endspiel.jpg|thumb|FC Schalke 04 supporters in 1941]]\nSchalke's first [[List of German football champions#German football championships under the Third Reich (1933\u201345)|national title]] came in [[1934 German football championship|1934]] with a 2\u20131 victory over favourites [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]]. [[1935 German football championship|The next year]], they successfully defended their title against [[VfB Stuttgart]] with a 6\u20134 win. The club missed the [[1936 German football championship|1936]] final, but would make appearances in the championship match in each of the next six years, coming away victorious in [[1937 German football championship|1937]], [[1939 German football championship|1939]], [[1940 German football championship|1940]] and [[1942 German football championship|1942]]. Three of those national finals were against Austrian teams \u2013 [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira Wien]], [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]] and [[First Vienna FC|First Vienna]] \u2013 which played in Germany's Gauliga Ostmark after Austria's incorporation into the Reich through the 1938 ''[[Anschluss]]''.\n\n''Die K\u00f6nigsblauen'' also made frequent appearances in the final of the Tschammerpokal, but enjoyed much less success there. They lost the [[1935 Tschammerpokal|inaugural Tschammerpokal]] 0\u20132 to 1. FC N\u00fcrnberg in 1935. They also made failed appearances in the [[1936 Tschammerpokal|1936]], [[1941 Tschammerpokal|1941]], and [[1942 Tschammerpokal|1942]] finals with their only victory coming in [[1937 Tschammerpokal|1937]] against Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf.\n\nOver a dozen seasons, from 1933 to 1945, Schalke won 162 of 189 Gauliga matches, drawing 21 and losing only 6. Within this period, they scored 924 goals and conceded just 145. From 1935 to 1939, they did not lose a single league match. The club's dominance throughout this period led them to be held up for propaganda purposes by the [[Nazism|Nazi]] regime as an example of \"new Germany\".\n\n===Post-war football===\n[[File:Kuzorra87.jpg|thumb|right|upright=.9|Commonly regarded as the greatest S04 player of all time alongside [[Fritz Szepan]], [[Ernst Kuzorra]] is also commonly regarded as one of the greatest German [[Forward (association football)|forwards]] and led S04 to become the dominant team in [[Football in Germany|German football]] winning six [[List of German football champions|German championships]] and one [[DFB-Pokal]] from 1934 to 1942. [[Ernst Kuzorra]] was one of the main axes of what became known as the \"'''Schalker Kreisel'''; a system that used quick and short [[Passing (association football)|passing]]\", to confuse and overwhelm the opponent.]]\nWith Germany in chaos towards the end of [[World War II]], Schalke played just two matches in 1945. They resumed regular play following the war and, for a time, continued to compete as a strong side. They set a record in a national championship round match with a 20\u20130 drubbing of [[2nd Oberliga West#Overview|SpVgg Herten]], but that spoke more to the weakened condition of German football than the ability of the team. Schalke's play fell off and the best they could manage in the new Oberliga West in 1947 was a sixth-place finish. Within two years, they slipped to 12th place.\n\nIt would take Schalke until the mid-1950s to recover their form. They finished third in a tight three-way race for the 1954 Oberliga West title, decided on the last day of the season. The following year, they appeared in the [[1954\u201355 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] final, where they lost 2\u20133 to [[Karlsruher SC]]. The club's next, and to date last, German championship came in [[German football championship 1958|1958]] with a 3\u20130 victory over [[Hamburger SV]]. The strong fanbase of the club is as well documented in a local church, St. Joseph, in Gelsenkirchen. It was renovated shortly after the 1958 victory, where one of the glass windows shows [[Aloysius Gonzaga]] with a football and the dress and colors of Schalke.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.derwesten.de/staedte/gelsenkirchen/der-fussball-heilige-wacht-ueber-die-st-joseph-kirche-in-schalke-id4859975.html |title=Der Fu\u00dfball-Heilige wacht \u00fcber die St.-Joseph-Kirche in Schalke |last=zur Nieden |first=Felix |date=12 July 2011 |website=WAZ |language=de |access-date=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Entry to the Bundesliga===\nSchalke continued to play well, delivering a number of top four finishes in the years leading up to the 1963 formation of the [[Bundesliga]], West Germany's new federal, professional league. Those results earned them selection as 1 of 16 clubs admitted to the top-flight league.\n\nTheir first years in the Bundesliga were difficult. In [[1964\u201365 Bundesliga|1964\u201365]], they escaped relegation only through the expansion of the league to 18 teams. A number of finishes at the lower end of the league table followed, before a marked improvement in [[1971\u201372 Bundesliga|1971\u201372]], culminating in a second-place finish to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and after having led the league for much of the season. In the same season, Schalke won the [[1971\u201372 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] for the second time in its history.\n\n===The Bundesliga scandal of 1971===\nDespite their improved results, the seeds of a major reversal had already been sown. A number of the team's players and officials were accused of accepting [[Bribes#Sport corruption|bribes]] as part of the widespread [[Bundesliga scandal (1971)|Bundesliga scandal of 1971]]. Investigation showed that Schalke had deliberately played to lose their 17 May, 28th-round match against [[Arminia Bielefeld]], 0\u20131. As a result, several Schalke players were banned for life, including three \u2013 [[Klaus Fischer]], [[Reinhard Libuda|\"Stan\" Libuda]] and [[Klaus Fichtel]] \u2013 who regularly played for the [[Germany national football team|West Germany national team]] at the time.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nEven though the penalties were later commuted to bans ranging from six months to two years, the scandal had a profound effect on what might have possibly become one of the dominant German teams of the 1970s.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n===Crisis and recovery===\n[[File:Internazionale-Schalke 04 1997-05-21.svg|thumb|FC Schalke 04 starting line-up in their victorious [[1997 UEFA Cup Final]].]]\nIn 1973, the club moved to the [[Parkstadion]], newly built for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] and having a capacity of 70,000 spectators. In the wake of the scandal, the club's performance was uneven. They managed another second-place result in [[1976\u201377 Bundesliga|1976\u201377]], finishing just one point behind champions [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]].\n\nIn the early 1980s, ''Die Knappen'' ran into trouble and found themselves relegated to the [[2. Bundesliga|second division of the Bundesliga]] for the 1981\u201382 season and, after promotion, again in 1983\u201384. They returned to the top flight in [[1984\u201385 Bundesliga|1984]] but slipped once more to the second tier in 1988. They returned to the Bundesliga in the [[1991\u201392 Bundesliga|1991\u201392]] season and have stayed in the top flight ever since.\n\nThe club earned their first honours since the DFB-Pokal win of [[1971\u201372 DFB-Pokal|1972]] with a victory in the final of the [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup]] over [[Inter Milan]] on penalties. Coached by the Dutch coach [[Huub Stevens]], the 1997 Schalke squad earned the nickname \"Euro Fighters\", which is still in use among fans. Stevens, who was widely unknown in Germany at the time, quickly earned himself a cult following among the Schalke supporters.\n\nStevens successfully implemented a system of rigid discipline, especially in the defence. His motto \"''Die Null mu\u00df stehen''\" (in [[English language|English]], \"It has to read nil\"), which emphasized his importance on his side not conceding any goals, has found its way into everyday language in Germany.\n\nThe turn of the millennium has seen much stronger performances from Schalke. During the 1990s and early 2000, the club underwent a successful transformation into a modern, commercial sports organization and established itself as one of the dominant teams of the Bundesliga. Schalke captured consecutive DFB-Pokals in [[2000\u201301 DFB-Pokal|2000\u201301]] and [[2001\u201302 DFB-Pokal|2001\u201302]], and earned second-place finishes in the Bundesliga in [[2000\u201301 Bundesliga|2000\u201301]], [[2004\u201305 Bundesliga|2004\u201305]] and [[2006\u201307 Bundesliga|2006\u201307]]. The [[2000\u201301 FC Schalke 04 season|2000\u201301]] season finish was heartbreaking for Schalke's supporters as it took a goal in the fourth minute of injury time by Bayern Munich away to Hamburger SV to snatch the title from ''Die K\u00f6nigsblauen''.\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220px\">\nFile:Schalke_Asamoah_06.jpg|Gerald Asamoah, longtime Schalke player with over 250 matches in over 11 years\nFile:Schalker Pokaljubel01.jpg|Schalke players celebrate winning the DFB-Pokal in 2002\n</gallery>\n\n===Current===\n{{Further|2013\u201314 FC Schalke 04 season|2014\u201315 FC Schalke 04 season}}\n[[File:Schalke 04 Fans 664.jpg|thumb|Fans displaying their colours at the [[Arena AufSchalke|Veltins-Arena]].]] The last few years have been more successful for Schalke, who finished in the second place in 2005, a result that led to Schalke making its second appearance in the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]. There, Schalke finished in third place during the group stage and continuing into the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], where they were eliminated by the eventual winners [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the semi-finals. In [[2005\u201306 Bundesliga|2005\u201306]], Schalke finished in fourth place in the Bundesliga and a year later they again finished as runners-up for the third time in seven seasons.\n\nIn the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League|2007\u201308 season]], Schalke progressed past the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage for the first time and advanced to the quarter-finals after defeating [[FC Porto|Porto]] on penalties in the round of 16. They were eliminated by [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the quarter-finals, losing both home and away matches 0\u20131.\n\nOn 9 October 2006, Russian oil company [[Gazprom]] became the club's new sponsor. The company stated it expected to invest as much as \u20ac125&nbsp;million in the club over a five-and-a-half-year period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/breakingnews/feedstory/0,,-6138335,00.html |title=ACTUAL ARTICLE TITLE BELONGS HERE! |website=The Guardian |access-date=4 February 2019}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gazprom's sponsorship has been seen by some analysts as a politically motivated attempt to buy friendship in Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article5458245.ece |title=Comment: Gazprom is not a market player, it\u2019s a political weapon |last=Boyes |first=Roger |date=7 January 2009 |work=[[The Times]] |access-date=7 January 2009 |location=London}}</ref> Within this sponsorship, Schalke 04 and [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]] signed a \"partnership agreement\"; both clubs intend to work closely on improving football-related issues.\n\nOn 13 April 2008, the club announced the dismissal of manager [[Mirko Slomka]] after a heavy defeat at the hands of [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] and elimination from the Champions League. Former players [[Mike B\u00fcskens]] and [[Youri Mulder]] were put in charge of the first team on an interim basis.\n\nFor the [[2008\u201309 Bundesliga|2008\u201309 Bundesliga season]], Schalke signed a new head coach, [[Fred Rutten]], previously of [[FC Twente|Twente]]. Rutten signed a contract running until June 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schalke04.com/news/single-view/artikel/rutten-named-new-schalke-boss.html |title=Rutten named new Schalke boss |date=23 April 2008 |website=FC Schalke 04 |access-date=16 August 2008}}</ref> In March 2009, Rutten was sacked and, once more, Mike B\u00fcskens, Youri Mulder and Oliver Reck took over the helm.\n\n[[File:Raul Gonzalez Blanco Schalke.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|[[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]], then all-time top goalscorer in European club competitions, played for Schalke from 2010 to 2012.]]\n\nOn 1 July 2009, [[Felix Magath]], who had led [[VfL Wolfsburg]] to the top of the table in the Bundesliga, became head coach and general manager of the ''K\u00f6nigsblauen''. The appointment of Magath as manager coincided with a multimillion-euro spending spree, allowing Schalke to acquire internationally-known forwards [[Klaas-Jan Huntelaar]] and [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]]. Magath's tenure at the club was initially successful, seeing the side score a glut of goals in the first few months of the season, though defensive frailties and Magath's questionable squad selection had made him unpopular with Schalke supporters by December 2010. On 16 March 2011, Magath was sacked and replaced with [[Ralf Rangnick]], who previously, between 2004 and 2005, had a brief spell being in charge of the team. Within just weeks of his appointment, Rangnick masterminded a 5\u20132 victory over Inter Milan at the [[San Siro]] during the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|quarter-finals]] of the Champions League. Schalke advanced to the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League#Semi-finals|semi-final]] where they lost 2\u20130 to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the first leg and 4\u20131 in the second leg.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/8474565/Schalke-0-Manchester-United-2-match-report.html |title=Schalke 0 Manchester United 2 |date=26 April 2011 |website=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=26 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2011, Ralf Rangnick announced his immediate resignation as head coach of Schalke 04 due to [[Burnout (psychology)|long-term exhaustion]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1683898.html |title=Rangnick steps aside at Schalke |date=22 September 2011 |access-date=22 September 2011 |publisher=[[UEFA]]}}</ref> Assistant coach Seppo Eichkorn coached the team as interim manager until the appointment of Huub Stevens on 27 September 2011. Stevens' contract was to run until 30 June 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schalke04.com/news/single-view/artikel/huub-stevens-new-schalke-coach.html |title=Huub Stevens new Schalke coach |date=27 September 2011 |website=Schalke Official Website}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Schalke04 Barcelona CL0708 02.jpg|thumb|right|FC Schalke 04 in the UEFA Champions League line-up against [[FC Barcelona]].]]\n\nDespite having legendary status among Schalke supporters, Stevens' return to Schalke was met with some scepticism as fans feared that Stevens, who coached Schalke to the 1997 UEFA Cup win with a rigidly defensive system, could abandon Rangnick's system of attacking play in favour of returning to his 1997 defensive antics.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schalker-block5.de/index.php?page=Thread&threadID=24777 |title=Herzlich willkommen zur\u00fcck, Huub Stevens |date=13 May 2012}}</ref> The doubts of the supporters proved unfounded. Although Schalke played a somewhat inconsistent season, they reached third place in the Bundesliga and therefore direct qualification for the UEFA Champions League.\n\nSchalke had an excellent start to the [[2012\u201313 Bundesliga|2012\u201313 Bundesliga season]], and worked their way to second place in the league by November, just behind Bayern Munich. On 20 October, Schalke traveled to [[Borussia Dortmund]] for matchday 8, and were able to defeat the home side 2\u20131 to secure their first league ''[[Revierderby]]'' win since February 2010 while securing a Champions League place by finishing in fourth place.\n\nIn the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League]] [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]], Schalke's opponents were [[FCSB]], [[FC Basel]] and [[Chelsea F.C.]]. Schalke ultimately finished the group stage in second place, behind Chelsea, and was eliminated in the round of 16 by [[Real Madrid CF]].\n\nThe most prominent Schalke addition was the arrival of [[Kevin-Prince Boateng]] from [[A.C. Milan|Milan]].<ref name=\"Schalke sign Kevin Prince Boateng\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/130830_boateng/page/509--86-86-.html |title=Schalke sign Kevin Prince Boateng |date=30 August 2013 |website=FC Schalke 04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901220119/http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/130830_boateng/page/509--86-86-.html |archive-date=1 September 2013 |access-date=3 August 2014}}</ref> After a disappointing first round of the [[2013\u201314 Bundesliga]] that saw Schalke in seventh place in the Bundesliga table, as well as an early exit from the [[2013\u201314 DFB-Pokal]] in the first knockout round, the club played their most successful second half of the season in club history. The season was marked by a glut of injuries to key squad players, including [[Jefferson Farf\u00e1n]] and Klaas-Jan Huntelaar, for almost the entire season. It also led to performance related discussions about head coach Jens Keller. Partially, Schalke fielded up to ten young players with potential who played in the Schalke youth system throughout the season. Among the brightest young player discoveries of the 2013\u201314 season were [[Max Meyer (footballer)|Max Meyer]] and [[Leon Goretzka]]. The young Schalke squad won 11 out of 17 matches, totalling 36 points. At the end of the 2013\u201314 season, the club finished in third place in the Bundesliga table to qualify for their third-straight UEFA Champions League appearance, a feat Schalke had never before achieved.\n\nOn 7 October 2014, after a 1\u20132 defeat to [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] and after amassing just eight points from seven matches, Keller was sacked and succeeded by [[Roberto Di Matteo]].<ref name=\"newswirengr.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://newswirengr.com/2014/10/07/schalke-announces-di-matteo-as-new-coach/ |title=Schalke Announces Di Matteo As New Coach |date=7 October 2014 |publisher=newswirengr.com |access-date=7 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{scha}}\n\n==Sponsors and finances==\n[[File:VeltinsArena at friendly Schalke 04 - Zenit St. Petersburg.JPG|thumb|right|Schalke 04 royal blue trademark [[Jersey (clothing)|jersey]] with sponsor Gazprom elaborately showcased prior to a match with Zenit Saint Petersburg at the Veltins-Arena to celebrate Gazprom's investment of over \u20ac125&nbsp;million in S04.]]\n{{Further|Forbes' list of the most valuable football clubs}}\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Gelsenkirchen - Schalker Feld - AufSchalke - Museum 05 ies.jpg|Exterior of the S04 museum at the S04 Veltins-Arena\nFile:Laola-Club Veltins-Arena.jpg|Restaurants at the S04 Veltins-Arena\nFile:Eroeffnungsspiel eishockey wm 2010.jpg|[[Ice hockey]] events are hosted at the S04 Veltins-Arena\nFile:Veltinsarena Biathlon.jpg|[[Biathlon]] and a variety of [[winter sport]] events are hosted at the S04 Veltins-Arena\n</gallery>\n\nThe headline sponsors of Schalke 04 are the China-based electronics manufacturer [[Hisense]] and the Russia-based hydrocarbon giant [[Gazprom]].<ref name=\"Vladimir Putin, Gazprom and Schalke 04\" /> Additional sponsors include Germany-based insurance group [[ERGO Insurance Group]]; Germany-based automotive manufacturer [[BMW]]; Germany-based motorcycle manufacturer [[BMW Motorrad]]; Spanish-based security insurance company [[Reale Seguros]]; China-based telecommunications company [[Huawei]]; cyber gambling and sports betting company [[bet-at-home.com]]; beverage company [[Coca-Cola]]; Germany-based brewery [[Veltins]]; and the current manufacturer of Schalke's squad kits, Germany-based [[Adidas]].<ref name=\"Vladimir Putin, Gazprom and Schalke 04\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/vladimir-putin-gazprom-and-schalke-04-how-russia-sending-troops-to-the-crimea-is-being-felt-in-the-bundesliga-9177403.html |title=Vladimir Putin, Gazprom and Schalke 04: How Russia sending troops to the Crimea is being felt in the Bundesliga |date=7 March 2014 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=3 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of operating income, Schalke possesses the seventh-highest operating income of any football club in the world at \u20ac48&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"Forbes List\" /> and 0% debt as of August 2014.<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\" /> Schalke generates the 12th-highest revenue of any football club in the world at \u20ac198&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\" />\n\nIn May 2014, Schalke 04 were ranked by ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine as the [[Forbes' list of the most valuable football clubs|12th-richest football club in the world]],<ref name=\"Forbes List\" /> at \u20ac446&nbsp;million, an increase of 16% from the previous year.<ref name=\"Schalke 04 - Forbes\" />\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Players==\n===Current squad===\n{{updated|22 January 2020|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://schalke04.de/en/funktion/team-en/ |title=First Team |website=FC Schalke 04 |access-date=1 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/fc-schalke-04-2/kader/1-bundesliga/2019-20 |title=FC Schalke 04 \u2013 Bundesliga: der Kader der Saison 2019/20 |website=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |trans-title=FC Schalke 04 \u2013 Bundesliga: the squad of the 2019-20 season |access-date=1 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=2  |nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Weston McKennie]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=3  |nat=ESP |pos=DF |name=[[Juan Miranda (footballer)|Juan Miranda]]|other=on loan from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=4  |nat=TUR |pos=DF |name=[[Ozan Kabak]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5  |nat=SRB |pos=DF |name=[[Matija Nastasi\u0107]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6  |nat=ESP |pos=MF |name=[[Omar Mascarell]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://schalke04.de/en/team/omar-mascarell-named-new-fc-schalke-04-captain/|title=Omar Mascarell named new FC Schalke 04 captain|website=FC Schalke 04|date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n{{Fs player|no=8  |nat=GER |pos=MF |name=[[Suat Serdar]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9  |nat=BEL |pos=FW |name=[[Benito Raman]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11 |nat=AUT |pos=FW |name=[[Michael Gregoritsch]]|other=on loan from [[FC Augsburg|Augsburg]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14 |nat=WAL |pos=FW |name=[[Rabbi Matondo]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15 |nat=TUR |pos=FW |name=[[Ahmed Kutucu]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=16 |nat=MAR |pos=MF |name=[[Nassim Boujellab]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=17 |nat=FRA |pos=DF |name=[[Benjamin Stambouli]]}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=18 |nat=GER |pos=MF |name=[[Daniel Caligiuri]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=19 |nat=AUT |pos=FW |name=[[Guido Burgstaller]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=20 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Jonjoe Kenny]]|other=on loan from [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21 |nat=FRA |pos=DF |name=[[Jean-Clair Todibo]]|other=on loan from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23 |nat=GER |pos=GK |name=[[Markus Schubert]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=24 |nat=GER |pos=DF |name=[[Bastian Oczipka]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25 |nat=MAR |pos=MF |name=[[Amine Harit]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=26 |nat=SEN |pos=DF |name=[[Salif San\u00e9]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=28 |nat=AUT |pos=MF |name=[[Alessandro Sch\u00f6pf]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=34 |nat=AUT |pos=GK |name=[[Michael Langer]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=35 |nat=GER |pos=GK |name=[[Alexander N\u00fcbel]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=37 |nat=GER |pos=MF |name=[[Levent Mercan]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=ALG|pos=MF |name=[[G IBRAHIM]]|other=at [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=DF |name=[[Jonas Carls]]|other=at [[FC Viktoria K\u00f6ln|Viktoria K\u00f6ln]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=GK |name=[[Ralf F\u00e4hrmann]]|other=at [[SK Brann]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=ESP|pos=DF |name=[[Pablo Insua]]|other=at [[SD Huesca]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=MAR|pos=DF |name=[[Hamza Mendyl]]|other=at [[Dijon FCO]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=MF |name=[[Sebastian Rudy]]|other=at [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] until June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=FW |name=[[Steven Skrzybski]]|other=at [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GHA|pos=FW |name=[[Bernard Tekpetey]]|other=at [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]] until 30 June 2021}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=FW |name=[[Cedric Teuchert]]|other=at [[Hannover 96]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=GER|pos=FW |name=[[Mark Uth]]|other=at [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n===Reserve team===\n{{main|FC Schalke 04 II}}\n\n===Notable former players===\n{{main|List of FC Schalke 04 players}}\n[[File:Grossplastik Schalke Koepfe 2001.jpg|thumb|right|Sculptures with some of the FC Schalke 04 \"Team of the Century\".]]\nIn the year 2000, the supporters voted for ''Schalker Jahrhundertelf'', the \"Team of the Century\":<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.derwesten.de/sport/schalkes-jahrhundertelf-id8114538.html |title=Schalkes Jahrhundertelf |publisher=derwesten.de |language=German |access-date=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=[[Norbert Nigbur]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Klaus Fichtel]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Olaf Thon]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Rolf R\u00fcssmann]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Fritz Szepan]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Ingo Anderbr\u00fcgge]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|pos=MF|nat=BEL|name=[[Marc Wilmots]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[Ernst Kuzorra]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[Klaus Fischer]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[Reinhard Libuda]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs player|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[R\u00fcdiger Abramczik]]<ref name=\"Schalkes Jahrhundertelf\" />}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Records===\n{{main|List of FC Schalke 04 records and statistics}}\n{{updated|1 October 2017}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tradition.schalke04.de/de/portraet/erfolge/rekordlisten/page/61--61--.html |title=Vereinstreue und Treffsicherheit: Die S04-Rekordlisten |website=FC Schalke 04 |language=de |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922055249/http://tradition.schalke04.de/de/portraet/erfolge/rekordlisten/page/61--61--.html |archive-date=22 September 2015 |access-date=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Klaus Fischer 2013-06-29.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Klaus Fischer]] scored the most goals in Schalke's Bundesliga history]]\n\n{{Col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+Most appearances (Bundesliga)\n!#!!class=\"unsortable\"|Nat.!!Player!!Apps\n|-\n|1||{{flagic