ctators.<ref name=\"Stadionkapazit\u00e4t\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/629918/artikel_schalke-erhoeht-stadionkapazitaet-um-knapp-300-plaetze.html |title=Schalke erh\u00f6ht Stadionkapazit\u00e4t |date=30 June 2015 |website=kicker.de |publisher=kicker |language=German |access-date=20 July 2015}}</ref> Schalke regularly draws sell-out crowds to what is widely regarded as one of the most modern and best multi-use facilities in Europe. The facility was previously known as the Arena AufSchalke and replaced the [[Parkstadion]] (capacity of 62,000) built in 1973. Prior to this, the club played its matches in the [[Gl\u00fcckauf-Kampfbahn]], constructed in 1928 with a capacity of 35,000. The facility was used for amateur matches during its later years with a reduced capacity of just 5,000.\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Veltins-Arena Panorama.jpg|An interior design panorama of the Veltins-Arena\nFile:2010-06-03_Arena_AufSchalke_20.jpg|Exterior of the Veltins-Arena\nFile:2010-06-04 Schalke 04-Gesch\u00e4ftsstelle 01.jpg|Training ground of FC Schalke 04 known as the Gesch\u00e4ftsstelle\n</gallery>\n\n==Fan culture==\n[[File:Schalke 04 Fans 677.jpg|thumb|left|S04 [[Ultras]] Gelsenkirchen.]]\n[[File:Schalker Massen01.jpg|thumb|right|S04 fans in the streets of Gelsenkirchen on a matchday.]]\nThe number of members of Schalke 04 grew from 10,000 in 1991 to 155,000 in 2018. {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} This figure makes Schalke 04 the second-biggest sports club in Germany and fourth-biggest sports club in the world, behind Bayern Munich, Sporting Lisbon and first-placed [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]. {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Schalke 04 has the fourth-largest fan-base of any team in the world. {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Schalke is currently ranked as the thirty-first-best football club in Europe and in Continental Europe by [[UEFA]]'s [[UEFA coefficient#UEFA Team Ranking|UEFA club rankings]].<ref name=\"UEFA Team Ranking 2020\">{{Cite web |url=https://kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl/bert/uefa/data/method5/trank2020.html |title=UEFA Team Ranking 2020 |publisher=kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl |access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> A representation of the Schalke 04 membership structure in 2014 showed, among other things, a female share of 20% and a share of the age group up to ten years of 14%.<ref name=\"Mitglied\" /> Around 30% of the members were not from North Rhine-Westphalia. Apart from Gelsenkirchen (10,197 members) and its immediate neighboring towns, the members of Schalke 04 also come from more distant cities such as [[Cologne]] (1,117), [[Berlin]] (932) and [[Dortmund]] (800).<ref name=\"Mitglied\" /> This high growth in Schalke 04 membership is also promoted by promotions of Schalke 04, as from 2013 to further \"advertise Schalke 04 brand\".<ref name=\"Mitglied\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.focus.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga1/bundesliga-schalke-freut-sich-ueber-80-000-vereins-mitglied_aid_436896.html |title=Schalke freut sich \u00fcber 80.000. Vereins-Mitglied |website=focus.de |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schalke04.de/de/mitglieder/mitgliedschaft/angebot/page/256--256--.html |title=Hand Drauf! Jetzt Mitglied werden! |website=schalke04.de |language=German |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719023855/http://www.schalke04.de/de/mitglieder/mitgliedschaft/angebot/page/256--256--.html |archive-date=19 July 2014 |access-date=3 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2013, Schalke 04 played their first home match of the 2013\u201314 season, a [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifier at the Veltins-Arena against the Greek runners-up [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] (led by former head coach Huub Stevens), drawing 1\u20131.<ref name=\"Streit um einsatz\" /> The match and result was more than overshadowed by a controversial police operation in the \"S04 Ultras Gelsenkirchen\" block of the Veltins-Arena against the fans of the home team with nearly 80 of the home team's fans injured.<ref name=\"Streit um einsatz\" /> The return match was won 3\u20132 by Schalke without any of their supporters allowed to attend the match.<ref name=\"Streit um einsatz\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/sport/fussball/bundesliga/streit-um-einsatz-gegen-saloniki-polizei-zieht-sich-aus-schalke-arena-zurueck-12570830.html |title=Streit um Einsatz gegen Saloniki - Polizei zieht sich aus Schalke-Arena zur\u00fcck |work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung |language=German}}</ref>\n\n===Schalke 04 Fan Club Association===\nSchalke 04 Fan Club Association (SFCV) is an umbrella organization, according to their own statement, has an estimated 1,500 fan clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfcv.de/ueber-uns.html |title=Von Fans f\u00fcr Fans |website=sfcv.de |language=German |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927232702/http://www.sfcv.de/ueber-uns.html |archive-date=27 September 2014 |access-date=3 August 2014}}</ref> Of those listed by the SFCV, 860 Schalke 04 fan clubs (October 2012) in which an estimated 200 were in Ruhr, 360 in the rest of North Rhine-Westphalia and 300 in the other federal states.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfcv.de/fanclub-liste.html |title=Fan-Clubs im Schalker Fan-Club Verband |website=sfcv.de |language=German |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926230939/http://www.sfcv.de/fanclub-liste.html |archive-date=26 September 2013 |access-date=3 August 2014}}</ref> A member of the board of SFCV has a permanent seat on the board of FC Schalke 04 and in 2013 SFCV merged with the \"Ultras Gelsenkirchen\" and later the supporters' club, Schalke Fan-Initiative eV with several members of strong fan groups from the SFCV, as is clear from the merger of the SFCV with the fan section of S04 has not adequately represented the fan interests.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reviersport.de/235317---schalke-supportersclub-tritt-aus.html |title=N\u00e4chster R\u00fcckschlag f\u00fcr den SFCV |website=reviersport.de |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fan-ini.de/blog/austritt-aus-dem-sfcv/ |title=Austritt aus dem SFCV |website=fan-ini.de |language=German}}</ref>\n\n===Friendships===\n[[File:Nuernberg Clubhaus 02.png|thumb|Friendship corner in the Fan Shop of the [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]] with trikots of Schalke 04.]]\nThe fan-base of Schalke is connected, in a friendly way, with the supporters of [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]] and Dutch club [[FC Twente|Twente]]. The friendship with N\u00fcrnberg is the oldest connection between two fan-bases in Germany. Before a match between both clubs, the official club songs are played.\n\n===Club songs===\n*''Blau und wei\u00df, wie lieb ich Dich'' (\"Blue and White, How I Love You\") is the official club song.\n*''Das Steigerlied'', traditional German mining song, play before every match.\n*''Blau und Wei\u00df ein Leben lang'' (\"Blue and white a life-long\") is the goal tune.\n*''K\u00f6nigsblauer S04'' (\"Royal Blue S04\") played after every match\n\nPopular unofficial [[football chants|chants]] are\n*''Der Mythos vom Schalker Markt'' (\"The Myth of the Schalke Market\"),\n*''Opa Pritschikowski'' (\"Grandpa Pritschikowski\"),\n*''Von der Emscher bis zum Bosporus'' (\"From the Emscher to the Bosphorus\"),\n*''Wir schlugen Roda...'' (\"We beat Roda...\"),\n*''Die Eurofighter sind wieder da'' (\"The Eurofighter are back again\"),\n*''F\u00fcr deine Farben leben und sterben wir'' (\"For your colours we live and die\"),\n*''Wir lieben alle nur den FC Schalke'' (\"We all love only FC Schalke\"),\n*''Wir sind die Fans'' (\"We are the fans\"),\n*''Hurra wir sind die Schalker Knappen'' (\"Hurray we are the Schalke [[Miner|Knappen]]\"),\n*''Kohle unter unser'n F\u00fc\u00dfen'' (\"Coal under our feet\"), and\n*''Steht auf, wenn ihr Schalker seid'' (\"Stand up if you're Schalke\"), sung to the melody of \"[[Go West (song)|Go West]]\" by the [[Pet Shop Boys]] (itself a cover of a [[Village People]] song).\n\n===Revierderby===\n{{Main|Revierderby}}\n\nThe Revierderby is the rivalry between local clubs Schalke 04 and [[Borussia Dortmund]], both situated in the densely populated [[Ruhr|Ruhr region]]. Because of the small geographical distances between the clubs (roughly 30 kilometers), fans of opposing clubs often meet in everyday life. The term may be used in any match between two football clubs of the Ruhr region (such as [[VfL Bochum]], [[Rot-Weiss Essen]] or [[MSV Duisburg]]), but the term is most commonly associated with the rivalry between Schalke and Dortmund due to the derby's popularity and prestige. To some fans, the win of the derby itself is more important than the actual performance in the Bundesliga.\n\n{{wide image|Revierderby.png|800px|align-cap=center|Revierderby results since the 1963\u201364 season}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:2010-06-03 Arena AufSchalke 07.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Cleat (shoe)|cleats]] worn by the entire S04 squad players in the 1920s displayed at the museum of Schalke 04.]]\nSchalke has been subject of a feature-length film called ''[[Fu\u00dfball ist unser Leben]]'' (\"Football is our life\"), shown in 1999. Actors [[Uwe Ochsenknecht]] and [[Ralf Richter (actor)|Ralf Richter]], both of whom were in the award-winning film ''[[Das Boot]]'' played the main roles, while many persons associated with Schalke had cameo roles, such as manager [[Rudi Assauer]], coaches Huub Stevens and Helmut Schulte, and player Yves Eigenrauch. Also featured were prominent fans like Manfred Breuckmann, Ulrich Potofski or DJ Hooligan.<ref name=\"sp\">''[http://www.filmspiegel.de/filme/filme.php?id=379 Fu\u00dfball ist unser Leben] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425083838/http://www.filmspiegel.de/filme/filme.php?id=379 |date=25 April 2012 }}'', review in ''FilmSpiegel'', 1999 (in German)</ref> The film is a comedy about \"Hans\", a Schalke fanatic, and his three pals who somehow get involved in kidnapping and trying to bring back to form the team's new star player \"Di Ospeo\" and in the process bet Hans' house that their idol will score in the final match.<ref name=sp /> Some critics considered ''Football is our life'' to be \"one of the worst German comedies ever\".<ref name=sp />\n\n\"Schalke\" is mentioned in the film ''Das Boot'' when the [[Boatswain|bosun]] tells the crew in their ward room, \"I got bad news for you men. Schalke lost 5\u20130, looks like we won't be in the final this year.\"\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Honours==\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://schalke04.de/en/club/milestones/ |title=Milestones |website=Schalke 04.de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://us.soccerway.com/teams/germany/fc-schalke-04/966/trophies/ |title=FC Schalke 04: Trophies |publisher=Soccerway}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic===\n[[File:Meisterschale Schalke-Museum.jpg|thumb|right|Schalke 04 have won the [[List of German football champions|German championship]] 7 times.]]\n[[File:Schalke DFBpokal schief2.jpg|thumb|upright|Schalke 04 won the [[DFB-Pokal]] 5 times, the last in the 2010\u201311 season. The picture shows the trophy in 2002, slightly leaning to one side after Schalke's team manager [[Rudi Assauer]] dropped it.]]\n'''[[List of German football champions|German Championship]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' (7) [[1934 German football championship|1934]], [[1935 German football championship|1935]], [[1937 German football championship|1937]], [[1939 German football championship|1939]], [[1940 German football championship|1940]], [[1942 German football championship|1942]], [[1958 German football championship|1958]]\n'''[[DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal/German Cup]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' (5) [[1937 Tschammerpokal|1937]], [[1971\u201372 DFB-Pokal|1971\u201372]], [[2000\u201301 DFB-Pokal|2000\u201301]], [[2001\u201302 DFB-Pokal|2001\u201302]], [[2010\u201311 DFB-Pokal|2010\u201311]]\n'''[[DFB-Ligapokal|DFB-Ligapokal/German League Cup]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' [[2005 DFL-Ligapokal|2005]]\n'''[[DFL-Supercup|DFL-Supercup/German Super Cup]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' [[2011 DFL-Supercup|2011]]\n'''[[2. Bundesliga]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' (2) [[1981\u201382 2. Bundesliga|1981\u201382]], [[1990\u201391 2. Bundesliga|1990\u201391]]\n\n===International===\n{{Further|FC Schalke 04 in European football}}\n'''[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup|1996\u201397]]\n'''[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' [[2003 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2003]], [[2004 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2004]]\n\n===UEFA club coefficient ranking===\n{{updated|22 August 2019|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/uefarankings/club/#/yr/2019 |title=Member associations \u2013 UEFA Coefficients \u2013 Club coefficients |publisher=UEFA }}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Nation !! Team !! Points\n|-\n|22||align=left|{{flagu|Spain}} || [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]||68.000\n|-\n|23||align=left|{{flagu|Ukraine}} || [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] ||65.000\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|24||align=left|{{flagu|Germany}} || Schalke ||63.000\n|-\n|25||align=left|{{flagu|Turkey}} || [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]||62.000\n|-\n|26||align=left|{{flagu|France}} || [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]||62.000\n|}\n\n===Youth===\n;Domestic\n'''[[Under 19 Bundesliga]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' 1976, 2006, 2012, 2015\n**'''Runners-up:''' 1975, 1980, 1981\n'''[[Under 19 Bundesliga#Division champions|Under 19 Bundesliga West]]'''\n*'''Winners (5):''' 2006, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015\n'''[[Under 17 Bundesliga]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' 1978, 2002\n**'''Runners-up:''' 1977, 1980\n'''[[Under 17 Bundesliga#League winners|Under 17 Bundesliga West]]'''\n*'''Winners:''' 2013\n\n===Double===\n*[[Double (association football)#Inter-war period|1937]]: [[1937 German football championship|Championship]] and [[1937 Tschammerpokal|Cup]]\n\n==Corporate structure==\n{{updated|1 July 2019}}\n\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#4169E1\"| <span style=\"color:white\">Managing board (executive members)</span>\n|-\n! Role !! Person\n|-\n|Marketing and communications || {{flagicon|GER}} [[:de:Alexander Jobst|Alexander Jobst]]\n|-\n|Finance and administration ||{{flagicon|GER}} [[Peter Peters (football official)|Peter Peters]]\n|-\n|Sport || {{flagicon|GER}} [[:de:Jochen Schneider (Fu\u00dfballfunktion\u00e4r)|Jochen Schneider]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|''Reference:<ref name=\"Managing Board\" />''\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#4169E1\"| <span style=\"color:white\">Supervisory board (non executive member)</span>\n|-\n! Role !! Person\n|-\n| Chairman || {{flagicon|GER}} [[:de:Clemens T\u00f6nnies|Clemens T\u00f6nnies]]\n|-\n| Vice chairman || {{flagicon|GER}} Dr. Jens Buchta\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| {{flagicon|GER}} Moritz D\u00f6rnemann\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| {{flagicon|GER}} Stefan Gesenhues\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| {{flagicon|GER}} Uwe Kemmer\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| {{flagicon|GER}} Ulrich K\u00f6llmann\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|GER}} Peter Lange\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|GER}} Dirk Metz\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Huub Stevens]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|GER}} Heiner T\u00fcmmers\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Matthias Warnig]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|''Reference:<ref name=\"Supervisory Board\" />''\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#4169E1\"|<span style=\"color:white\">Coaching Staff</span>\n|-\n! Role !! Person\n|-\n| Head coach || {{flagicon|USA}} [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]]\n|-\n| Assistant coach || {{flagicon|GER}} Christoph B\u00fchler\n|-\n| Assistant coach || {{flagicon|GER}} Frank Fr\u00f6hling\n|-\n| Assistant coach || {{flagicon|GER}} Matthias Kreutzer\n|-\n| Goalkeeping coach || {{flagicon|GER}} [[Simon Henzler]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Athletics coach || {{flagicon|LUX}} Bob Schoos\n|-\n| {{flagicon|AUT}} Klaus Luisser\n|-\n| Analyst || {{flagicon|GER}} Lars Gerling\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\