ad Hayri \u00dcrg\u00fcpl\u00fc]]\n* [[Nihat Erim]]\n}}\n\n;Foreign Prime Ministers\n\n*[[David Ben-Gurion]], Prime Minister of [[Israel]]\n*[[Moshe Sharett]], Prime Minister of [[Israel]]\n\n;Turkish Ministers\n\n* [[Mehmet Ali \u015eahin]]\n* [[Cemil \u00c7i\u00e7ek]]\n\n;Journalists \n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[U\u011fur D\u00fcndar]]\n* [[Abdi \u0130pek\u00e7i]]\n* [[Halit K\u0131van\u00e7]]\n* [[Nedim \u015eener]]\n* [[Ahmet \u015e\u0131k]]\n* [[Metin Toker]]\n* [[Hrant Dink]]\n}}\n\n;Scientists\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Hulusi Behcet]]\n* [[Aykut Barka]]\n* [[Alp Ikizler]]\n* [[Ahmet Mete I\u015f\u0131kara]]\n* [[Muzafer Sherif|Muzaffer \u015eerif]]\n* [[Zeynel Mungan]]\n* [[Aziz Sancar]], [[Nobel Prize|Nobel Laureate]] in Chemistry\n* [[Nazim Terzioglu]]\n}}\n\n;Writers\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Nihal Atsiz]]\n*[[Ali Kurumahmut]]\n*[[Orhan Pamuk]], [[Nobel Prize|Nobel Laureate]] in Literature\n*[[\u0130lhan Sel\u00e7uk]]<ref name=nt>{{cite news |title=Turkish journalist \u0130lhan Sel\u00e7uk died|url= http://www.nationalturk.com/en/turkish-journalist-ilhan-selcuk-died-539647|work=National Turk|date=2008-06-23 |accessdate=2010-07-06}}</ref>\n*[[Ahmet Hamdi Tanpinar]]\n*[[Bahadir Kaleagasi]], international co-ordinator of [[Turkish Industrialists' and Businessmen's Association|TUSIAD]]\n}}\n\n;Poets\n\n*[[Orhan Veli]]\n*[[Attila \u0130lhan]]\n*[[Onat Kutlar]]\n\n;Musicians\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Mercan Dede]]\n*[[Sadettin Kaynak]]\n*[[Arif Mardin]]\n*[[B\u00fclent Orta\u00e7gil]]\n}}\n\n;Medicine\n\n*[[Masud Sabri]] \u2013 Pharmacist and former Governor of Xinjiang province in China\n\n;Other\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[\u00d6zg\u00fcr \u00c7evik]] \u2013 Singer, Actor\n*[[C\u00fcneyt Ark\u0131n]] \u2014 Actor, Director\n*[[Cansu Dere]] \u2013 Actress, Model\n*[[Burcu Esmersoy]]<ref>{{cite news |last=\u0130pek |first=B\u00fclent |date=1 January 2011 |title=O Art\u0131k Bir Magazin Fig\u00fcr\u00fc |url=http://magazin.haberturk.com/herkes-bunu-konusuyor/haber/587013-sekreterdi-miss-turkeyde-4-oldu-tvde-parladi-dansla-dorukta |url-status= |newspaper=[[HaberT\u00fcrk]] |location=Istanbul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803235959/http://magazin.haberturk.com/herkes-bunu-konusuyor/haber/587013-sekreterdi-miss-turkeyde-4-oldu-tvde-parladi-dansla-dorukta |archive-date=3 August 2014 |access-date=10 August 2016}}</ref> \u2013 Anchorwoman, Model\n*[[Deniz Gezmi\u015f]] \u2013 Political activist\n*[[\u00d6zg\u00fc Namal]] \u2013 Actress, Singer\n*[[T\u00fcrkan Rado]] (1915-2007), first ever Turkish female professor of jurisprudence\n*[[\u00c7a\u011fatay Ulusoy]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Okan Yalab\u0131k]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Ekrem \u0130mamo\u011flu]] \u2013 Mayor of Istanbul\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Balkan Universities Network]]\n* {{interlanguage link|Famous Academicians and Persons of Istanbul University|de|Liste ber\u00fchmter Pers\u00f6nlichkeiten der Universit\u00e4t Istanbul}}\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n* [[Istanbul University Observatory]]\n* [[Beyaz\u0131t Tower]]\n* [[Education in the Ottoman Empire]]\n* [[Dar ul-Funun (Persia)]]\n\n* {{Portal-inline|Turkey}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Istanbul University}}\n* [http://www.istanbul.edu.tr/ Istanbul University website] {{in lang|tr|en}}\n* [http://www.istanbul.edu.tr/tarihce.php History of Istanbul University (Turkish)]\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Istanbul}}\n{{Fatih}}\n{{Universities in Turkey}}\n{{Balkan Universities Network}}\n{{Coimbra Group}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Istanbul University| ]]\n[[Category:1874 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ottoman architecture in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Universities established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Fatih]]\n[[Category:Avc\u0131lar]]\n[[Category:1453 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 15th century]]\n", "name_user": "Mertsalman", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istanbul_University"}
{"title_page": "Kosala (novel)", "text_new": "{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Kosala\n| title_orig    = \u0915\u094b\u0938\u0932\u093e\n| translator    = Sudhakar Marathe\n| image         = Cocoon Bhalchandra Nemade.jpeg\n| caption       = Cover of English translation \n| author        = [[Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[India]]\n| language      = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| subject       = [[Existentialism]], [[Social alienation|alienation]]\n| genre         = \n| set_in        = 1950s [[Khandesh]] ([[Central India]]) and [[Pune]]\n| publisher     = Popular Publications<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\">{{cite book|first=Anjali|last=Nerlekar|title=Bombay Modern: Arun Kolatkar and Bilingual Literary Culture|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/45382|year=2016|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-3275-7|page=274|via=[[Project MUSE]]}}{{Subscription required}}</ref>\n| pub_date      = September 1963\n| english_pub_date = 1997\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = \n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 38258018\n}}\n\n'''''Kosala''''' ({{lang-en|Cocoon}}), sometimes spelled '''''Kosla''''', is a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] novel by Indian writer [[Bhalchandra Nemade]], published in [[1963 in literature|1963]]. At the time of its publication, he was 25. Regarded as Nemade's [[magnum opus]], and accepted as a modern classic of [[Marathi literature]], the novel uses the [[Autobiographical novel|autobiographical form]] to narrate the journey of a young man, Pandurang Sangvikar, and his friends through his college years. Since its publication, the novel has been considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-ended nature and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been translated into eight Indian languages, and into English.\n\n==Publication==\n''Kosala'' is Bhalchandra Nemade's [[debut novel]], written it over a two-week period in 1963 when he was twenty-five. It was published in September of the same year, and quickly became a success. Several editions appeared in the following years, and its twenty-second edition was published in 2013.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\">{{cite journal|last=Chitre|first=Dilip|author-link=Dilip Chitre|title=Alienation in Four Marathi Novels|year=1969|journal=Humanist Review|publisher=Modern Education Foundation|publication-place=Bombay|volume=1|issue=2|page=161\u2013175|oclc=1752400}}</ref><ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\">{{cite book|last=Gurjarpadhye-Khanderparkar|first=Prachi|title=Reinventing the Self: Nativist Cultural Imagination of \"Kosla\"|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=July\u2013August 2014|volume=58|issue=4|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=172\u2013185|jstor=44753804}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Contents==\nWith the use of [[first-person narrative]] technique, the novel deals with the first twenty-five years of the life of Pandurang Sangavikar,<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> a young man with rural upbringing who moves to [[Pune]] for higher education. He feels isolated in his new social setting. Due to persistent feeling of estrangement, he returns home, only to encounter further disillusionment, where he experiences his sister's death, his father's domination and his own financial dependence.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\">{{cite book|author1=Nalini Natarajan|author2=Emmanuel Sampath Nelson|title=Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&pg=PA233|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport|isbn=978-0-313-28778-7|page=233}}</ref> The novel try to encompass the whole social spectrum from the point of view of the young boy, Pandurang.<ref name=\"Hatkanagalekar1980\">{{cite journal|last=Hatkanagalekar|first=M.D.|title=Marathi: A Desirable Advance|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=November-December 1980|volume=23|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|issue=6|page=146|jstor=23330269}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nPrincipal characters are:<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|title=Masterpieces of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dXFOAAAAYAAJ|volume=|year=1997|publisher=[[National Book Trust]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-237-1978-8|page=875\u2013877}}</ref>\n* Pandurang Sangavikar \u2013 a protagonist and the only son of a rich village farmer; hostel students call him by his short name, Pandu.\n* Pandurang's father \u2013 head of a joint family, a rich and respected man in his village\n* Mani \u2013 Pandurang's younger sister\n* Giridhar \u2013 Pandurang's village friend\n* Suresh Bapat \u2013 Pandurang's college friend in Pune\n\n==Plot==\nThe story occurs in [[Khandesh]], a geographic region in [[Central India]], and in Pune, and takes place during 1950s.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nDivided into six sections, the novel narrates, using autobiographical form, the life-story of Pandurang Sangvikar, a young man of 25. Pandurang is the son of well-to-do farmer from Sangvi, a village in Khandesh. The joint family he comes from includes, apart from his parents, his grandmother and four sisters. Pandurang has had a peculiar relationship with his father who is the typical example of a patriarchal family head. He finds his father extremely money-minded, materialistic in pursuits, selfish, unscrupulous and dictatorial in attitude. He does not allow Pandurang, as a boy, to learn to play flute or to act in plays staged at school. He beats his son for wandering around in the company of friends. Thus, right from his childhood, Pandurang is estranged from his father. In sharp contrast to his relationship with his father, Pandurang has extreme affection for his mother and his sisters.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nAfter passing his matriculation examination from the local school, Pandurang moves to [[Pune]] for his college education.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> Living in a hostel, Pandurang decides to enjoy college life. For this he becomes the secretary of the debating society of the college, prefect of the hostel and also directs a play at the Annual Day function of the college. In good faith he gives the management of the hostel mess to one of his poor deserving friends. Though Pandurang tries to help everybody around he eventually finds that he is being used by his so-called friends. Finally when he fails badly in the examinations and his financial position worsens, his life-style invites the wrath of his father. Pandurang then learns the lesson that good deeds do not count for much in life.<ref name=\"George1993\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|editor-link=K. M. George (writer)|title=Modern Indian Literature: an Anthology: Fiction|volume=Vol. 2|year=1993|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7201-506-2|page=745}}</ref>\n\nPandurang is a totally new man in the second year of college. He is carefree and adventurous. Now even his father is hesitant to ask him to mend his ways. The untimely death of his younger sister, Mani, somewhat shakes him but otherwise he does not care for anything. Consequently, he fails in the examination. Pandurang, trying in vain to find employment in the city, ultimately returns to his village with an 'existentially' vacant mind. He is now one among the many unemployed youngsters of the village. As he tries to understand their view of life, their sorrows and happiness, the real meaning of life gradually starts dawning on Pandurang.<ref name=\"George1993\"/>\n\n==Theme and techniques==\nThe main theme of ''Kosala'' is [[Social alienation|alienation]].<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel is also influenced by [[existential philosophy]],<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> as the ideas of existentialism such as obsession of birth and death, dread, alienation, and absurdity are clearly exposed in it. Similar to other existential novels, Kosla also explores the life of an individual and disclose numerous questions regarding the [[meaning of life]] and the values of existence. As seen in the existential novels, here also, Pandurang tells his life story from the [[first person point of view]]. ''Kosala'' is considered as the first existential novel in Marathi literature.<ref>{{cite thesis|first=Dattatraya Dnyandev|last=Khaladkar |title=Existentialism in the Selected American and Marathi Novels: a Comparative Study|chapter=Existentialism in Marathi Novels |chapter-url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/9899/7/07_chapter%203.pdf |year=2010 |publisher=Department of English, Shivaji University |location=Kolhapur|type=Ph.D|pages=144\u2013145|hdl=10603/9899}}</ref>\n\nPandurang, the protagonist, has been seen as 'quintessential anti-hero',<ref name=\"Padgaonkar1997\">{{cite journal|last=Padgaonkar|first=Latika|title=Cocoon by Bhalchandra Nemade (Book Review)|journal=The Book Review|volume=21|year=1997|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|location=New Delhi|page=42|oclc=564170386}}</ref> who refuses to take all forms of colonial modernity: literacy, wester education, urbanisation, industrialisation, capitalism and nationalism and the values of \"progress\" emanating from them.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/>\n\nPandurang is estranged from his father, right from his childhood. Later on in the novel, this estrangement develops into a major theme of mute revolt on the part of the younger generation, against the patriarchal system of values so characteristic of traditional Indian life. Pandurang has not so far found anything meaningful in his experience of village life. The same experience of meaninglessness repeats itself in his college life too in Pune, spread over six years.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe novel has been written in an epistolary fashion, where it reads like a number of diary entries. The language of the protagonist, Sangvikar, is an instrument in divulging his worldview. He uses a Marathi dialect spoken in rural Maharashtra. Despite the pessimistic undertones, there is an element of humour throughout the novel.  Another technique employed by the author is that the narration describes \"historical investigations\" often undertaken by Sangvikar and his friend Suresh Bapat, which ultimately uncover to them the absurdity and pathos of their conditions.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It uses oblique, irrelevant humour as a serious moral strategy to unmask the phoneyness of society and culture.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe narrative of the novel fuses different types of genres such as the autobiography, the diary, the novel, the Indian folktales, folk narratives, and medieval saint literature. The language used in the novel are standard, archaic, urban, non-urban dialects, slangs, jargons, and sometimes poetic and rhetoric.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/> ''Kosala'' is said to have been inspired partially by [[J. D. Salinger]]'s ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''.<ref name=\"Sarang1992\">{{cite journal|last=Sarang|first=Vilas|title=Tradition and Conflict in the Context of Marathi Literature|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=September\u2013October 1992|volume=35|issue=5|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=159\u2013168|jstor=23337173}} {{closed access}}</ref> The narration style is similar as that of ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref name=\"Nandgaonkar 2015\">{{cite web|last=Nandgaonkar|first=Satish|title=Marathi Novelist Bhalchandra Nemade Chosen for Jnanpith Award|website=The Hindu|date=6 February 2015|url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/marathi-novelist-bhalchandra-nemade-chosen-for-jnanpith-award/article6865738.ece|access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Kosala'' is widely regarded as a modern classic<ref name=\"DattaLal1991\">{{cite book|last=Lal|first=Mohan|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: Navaratri-Sarvasena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOsbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-260-1003-1|ignore-isbn-error=true|pages=27, 274}}</ref> and a path-breaking novel<ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | title=Jnanpith award for Marathi author Bhalchandra Nemade - india | website=Hindustan Times | date=7 February 2015| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/jnanpith-award-for-marathi-author-bhalchandra-nemade/story-Q1mRTvFdbJOnX9DpuUfTeK.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> which left its mark on the ''sathottari'' (post-1960) Marathi fiction.<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\"/> With its publication, Nemade was considered a representative writer of his generation.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel received immediate critical acclaim after its publication and heralded a new trend in Marathi literature.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> Since its publication the novel is considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-endedness and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been the most appreciated and widely interpreted novel by critics including [[Dilip Chitre]], [[Narhar Ambadas Kurundkar|Narhar Kurundkar]], Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar, [[Vilas Sarang]], Sukanya Aagase, Rekha Inamdar-Sane and  Vasudev Sawant. Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar wrote that, \"It was only ''Kosla'', which responding as it did to a crisis in the cultural consciousness of [[Maharashtra]], that opened up new, native possibilities of form and meaning and thus sought to change the direction of both literary taste and fictional tradition\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Digole|first=D. P.|title=Bhalchandra Nemade's Kosla: A Narrative of Revolt and Trapped Anguish|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=78295873&site=lrc-plus|journal=Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies|date=July 2012|volume=3|issue=3|pages=21\u201329|issn=0976-0814|via=[[EBSCO Information Services|Literary Reference Center Plus]]}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n''Kosala'' has been adapted into a play, ''Me, Pandurang Sangavikar'' ({{abbr|lit.|literally}} I am Pandurang Sangavikar), directed by Mandar Deshpande.<ref name=\"Banerjee 2016\">{{cite web | last=Banerjee | first=Kaushani | title=Pratibimb Marathi Natya Utsav: A mix of commercial and experimental plays - art and culture | website=Hindustan Times | date=31 July 2016 | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/pratibimb-marathi-natya-utsav-a-mix-of-commercial-and-experimental-plays/story-U4aGM5aNQhQvt5FxqRJR3L.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n''Kosala'' has been translated into eight Indian languages and also into English. The available translations of the novel are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Title !! Languge !! Translator !! Year !! Publisher !! Ref.\n|-\n| ''Cocoon'' || English  || Sudhakar Marathe || 1997 || Macmillan Publishers India, Chennai ||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KyHhAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|page=31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Hindi]] || - || 1983 || [[National Book Trust]], [[New Delhi]] ||\n|-\n| ''Kosheto'' || [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] || Usha Sheth || 1995  || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Kannada]] || Vaman Dattatraya Bendre || 1995 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||<ref name=\"Dutt1999\">{{cite book|author=Kartik Chandra Dutt|title=Who's who of Indian Writers, 1999: A-M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QA1V7sICaIwC&pg=PA127|year=1999|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-0873-5|page=127}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Palur Vah'' || [[Assamese language|Assamese]] || - || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] || Ajit Singh || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Need'' || [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || Vandana Alase Hazra || 2001 || [[Sahitya Akademi]], [[New Delhi]] ||<ref name=\"Rao2004\">{{cite book|last=Rao|first=D. S.|title=Five Decades: The National Academy of Letters, India : a Short History of Sahitya Akademi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JDsBBDoMccC&pg=PA11|year=2004|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-2060-7|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Urdu]] || - || 2002 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Koshapok'' || [[Odia language|Odia]] || - || 2005 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Google books|id=ywj6VehHd5oC}} (Marathi)\n* {{Google books|id=ue41AAAAMAAJ}} (Hindi translation)\n\n[[Category:1963 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n[[Category:Marathi novels]]\n[[Category:Existentialist novels]]\n[[Category:1963 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:1963 debut novels]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographical novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Kosala\n| title_orig    = \u0915\u094b\u0938\u0932\u093e\n| translator    = Sudhakar Marathe\n| image         = Cocoon Bhalchandra Nemade.jpeg\n| caption       = Cover of English translation \n| author        = [[Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[India]]\n| language      = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| subject       = [[Existentialism]], [[Social alienation|alienation]]\n| genre         = \n| set_in        = 1950s [[Khandesh]] ([[Central India]]) and [[Pune]]\n| publisher     = Popular Publications<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\">{{cite book|first=Anjali|last=Nerlekar|title=Bombay Modern: Arun Kolatkar and Bilingual Literary Culture|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/45382|year=2016|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-3275-7|page=274|via=[[Project MUSE]]}}{{Subscription required}}</ref>\n| pub_date      = September 1963\n| english_pub_date = 1997\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = \n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 38258018\n}}\n\n'''''Kosala''''' ({{lang-en|Cocoon}}), sometimes spelled '''''Kosla''''', is a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] novel by Indian writer [[Bhalchandra Nemade]], published in [[1963 in literature|1963]]. At the time of its publication, he was 25. Regarded as Nemade's [[magnum opus]], and accepted as a modern classic of [[Marathi literature]], the novel uses the [[Autobiographical novel|autobiographical form]] to narrate the journey of a young man, Pandurang Sangvikar, and his friends through his college years. Since its publication, the novel has been considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-ended nature and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been translated into eight Indian languages, and into English.\n\n==Publication==\n''Kosala'' is Bhalchandra Nemade's [[debut novel]], written it over a two-week period in 1963, when he was twenty-five. It was published in September of the same year, and quickly became a success. Several editions appeared in the following years, and its twenty-second edition was published in 2013.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\">{{cite journal|last=Chitre|first=Dilip|author-link=Dilip Chitre|title=Alienation in Four Marathi Novels|year=1969|journal=Humanist Review|publisher=Modern Education Foundation|publication-place=Bombay|volume=1|issue=2|page=161\u2013175|oclc=1752400}}</ref><ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\">{{cite book|last=Gurjarpadhye-Khanderparkar|first=Prachi|title=Reinventing the Self: Nativist Cultural Imagination of \"Kosla\"|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=July\u2013August 2014|volume=58|issue=4|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=172\u2013185|jstor=44753804}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Contents==\nWith the use of [[first-person narrative]] technique, the novel deals with the first twenty-five years of the life of Pandurang Sangavikar,<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> a young man with rural upbringing who moves to [[Pune]] for higher education. He feels isolated in his new social setting. Due to persistent feeling of estrangement, he returns home, only to encounter further disillusionment, where he experiences his sister's death, his father's domination and his own financial dependence.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\">{{cite book|author1=Nalini Natarajan|author2=Emmanuel Sampath Nelson|title=Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&pg=PA233|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport|isbn=978-0-313-28778-7|page=233}}</ref> The novel try to encompass the whole social spectrum from the point of view of the young boy, Pandurang.<ref name=\"Hatkanagalekar1980\">{{cite journal|last=Hatkanagalekar|first=M.D.|title=Marathi: A Desirable Advance|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=November-December 1980|volume=23|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|issue=6|page=146|jstor=23330269}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nPrincipal characters are:<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|title=Masterpieces of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dXFOAAAAYAAJ|volume=|year=1997|publisher=[[National Book Trust]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-237-1978-8|page=875\u2013877}}</ref>\n* Pandurang Sangavikar \u2013 a protagonist and the only son of a rich village farmer; hostel students call him by his short name, Pandu.\n* Pandurang's father \u2013 head of a joint family, a rich and respected man in his village\n* Mani \u2013 Pandurang's younger sister\n* Giridhar \u2013 Pandurang's village friend\n* Suresh Bapat \u2013 Pandurang's college friend in Pune\n\n==Plot==\nThe story occurs in [[Khandesh]], a geographic region in [[Central India]], and in Pune, and takes place during 1950s.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nDivided into six sections, the novel narrates, using autobiographical form, the life-story of Pandurang Sangvikar, a young man of 25. Pandurang is the son of well-to-do farmer from Sangvi, a village in Khandesh. The joint family he comes from includes, apart from his parents, his grandmother and four sisters. Pandurang has had a peculiar relationship with his father who is the typical example of a patriarchal family head. He finds his father extremely money-minded, materialistic in pursuits, selfish, unscrupulous and dictatorial in attitude. He does not allow Pandurang, as a boy, to learn to play flute or to act in plays staged at school. He beats his son for wandering around in the company of friends. Thus, right from his childhood, Pandurang is estranged from his father. In sharp contrast to his relationship with his father, Pandurang has extreme affection for his mother and his sisters.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nAfter passing his matriculation examination from the local school, Pandurang moves to [[Pune]] for his college education.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> Living in a hostel, Pandurang decides to enjoy college life. For this he becomes the secretary of the debating society of the college, prefect of the hostel and also directs a play at the Annual Day function of the college. In good faith he gives the management of the hostel mess to one of his poor deserving friends. Though Pandurang tries to help everybody around he eventually finds that he is being used by his so-called friends. Finally when he fails badly in the examinations and his financial position worsens, his life-style invites the wrath of his father. Pandurang then learns the lesson that good deeds do not count for much in life.<ref name=\"George1993\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|editor-link=K. M. George (writer)|title=Modern Indian Literature: an Anthology: Fiction|volume=Vol. 2|year=1993|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7201-506-2|page=745}}</ref>\n\nPandurang is a totally new man in the second year of college. He is carefree and adventurous. Now even his father is hesitant to ask him to mend his ways. The untimely death of his younger sister, Mani, somewhat shakes him but otherwise he does not care for anything. Consequently, he fails in the examination. Pandurang, trying in vain to find employment in the city, ultimately returns to his village with an 'existentially' vacant mind. He is now one among the many unemployed youngsters of the village. As he tries to understand their view of life, their sorrows and happiness, the real meaning of life gradually starts dawning on Pandurang.<ref name=\"George1993\"/>\n\n==Theme and techniques==\nThe main theme of ''Kosala'' is [[Social alienation|alienation]].<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel is also influenced by [[existential philosophy]],<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> as the ideas of existentialism such as obsession of birth and death, dread, alienation, and absurdity are clearly exposed in it. Similar to other existential novels, Kosla also explores the life of an individual and disclose numerous questions regarding the [[meaning of life]] and the values of existence. As seen in the existential novels, here also, Pandurang tells his life story from the [[first person point of view]]. ''Kosala'' is considered as the first existential novel in Marathi literature.<ref>{{cite thesis|first=Dattatraya Dnyandev|last=Khaladkar |title=Existentialism in the Selected American and Marathi Novels: a Comparative Study|chapter=Existentialism in Marathi Novels |chapter-url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/9899/7/07_chapter%203.pdf |year=2010 |publisher=Department of English, Shivaji University |location=Kolhapur|type=Ph.D|pages=144\u2013145|hdl=10603/9899}}</ref>\n\nPandurang, the protagonist, has been seen as 'quintessential anti-hero',<ref name=\"Padgaonkar1997\">{{cite journal|last=Padgaonkar|first=Latika|title=Cocoon by Bhalchandra Nemade (Book Review)|journal=The Book Review|volume=21|year=1997|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|location=New Delhi|page=42|oclc=564170386}}</ref> who refuses to take all forms of colonial modernity: literacy, wester education, urbanisation, industrialisation, capitalism and nationalism and the values of \"progress\" emanating from them.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/>\n\nPandurang is estranged from his father, right from his childhood. Later on in the novel, this estrangement develops into a major theme of mute revolt on the part of the younger generation, against the patriarchal system of values so characteristic of traditional Indian life. Pandurang has not so far found anything meaningful in his experience of village life. The same experience of meaninglessness repeats itself in his college life too in Pune, spread over six years.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe novel has been written in an epistolary fashion, where it reads like a number of diary entries. The language of the protagonist, Sangvikar, is an instrument in divulging his worldview. He uses a Marathi dialect spoken in rural Maharashtra. Despite the pessimistic undertones, there is an element of humour throughout the novel.  Another technique employed by the author is that the narration describes \"historical investigations\" often undertaken by Sangvikar and his friend Suresh Bapat, which ultimately uncover to them the absurdity and pathos of their conditions.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It uses oblique, irrelevant humour as a serious moral strategy to unmask the phoneyness of society and culture.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe narrative of the novel fuses different types of genres such as the autobiography, the diary, the novel, the Indian folktales, folk narratives, and medieval saint literature. The language used in the novel are standard, archaic, urban, non-urban dialects, slangs, jargons, and sometimes poetic and rhetoric.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/> ''Kosala'' is said to have been inspired partially by [[J. D. Salinger]]'s ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''.<ref name=\"Sarang1992\">{{cite journal|last=Sarang|first=Vilas|title=Tradition and Conflict in the Context of Marathi Literature|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=September\u2013October 1992|volume=35|issue=5|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=159\u2013168|jstor=23337173}} {{closed access}}</ref> The narration style is similar as that of ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref name=\"Nandgaonkar 2015\">{{cite web|last=Nandgaonkar|first=Satish|title=Marathi Novelist Bhalchandra Nemade Chosen for Jnanpith Award|website=The Hindu|date=6 February 2015|url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/marathi-novelist-bhalchandra-nemade-chosen-for-jnanpith-award/article6865738.ece|access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Kosala'' is widely regarded as a modern classic<ref name=\"DattaLal1991\">{{cite book|last=Lal|first=Mohan|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: Navaratri-Sarvasena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOsbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-260-1003-1|ignore-isbn-error=true|pages=27, 274}}</ref> and a path-breaking novel<ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | title=Jnanpith award for Marathi author Bhalchandra Nemade - india | website=Hindustan Times | date=7 February 2015| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/jnanpith-award-for-marathi-author-bhalchandra-nemade/story-Q1mRTvFdbJOnX9DpuUfTeK.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> which left its mark on the ''sathottari'' (post-1960) Marathi fiction.<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\"/> With its publication, Nemade was considered a representative writer of his generation.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel received immediate critical acclaim after its publication and heralded a new trend in Marathi literature.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> Since its publication the novel is considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-endedness and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been the most appreciated and widely interpreted novel by critics including [[Dilip Chitre]], [[Narhar Ambadas Kurundkar|Narhar Kurundkar]], Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar, [[Vilas Sarang]], Sukanya Aagase, Rekha Inamdar-Sane and  Vasudev Sawant. Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar wrote that, \"It was only ''Kosla'', which responding as it did to a crisis in the cultural consciousness of [[Maharashtra]], that opened up new, native possibilities of form and meaning and thus sought to change the direction of both literary taste and fictional tradition\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Digole|first=D. P.|title=Bhalchandra Nemade's Kosla: A Narrative of Revolt and Trapped Anguish|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=78295873&site=lrc-plus|journal=Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies|date=July 2012|volume=3|issue=3|pages=21\u201329|issn=0976-0814|via=[[EBSCO Information Services|Literary Reference Center Plus]]}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n''Kosala'' has been adapted into a play, ''Me, Pandurang Sangavikar'' ({{abbr|lit.|literally}} I am Pandurang Sangavikar), directed by Mandar Deshpande.<ref name=\"Banerjee 2016\">{{cite web | last=Banerjee | first=Kaushani | title=Pratibimb Marathi Natya Utsav: A mix of commercial and experimental plays - art and culture | website=Hindustan Times | date=31 July 2016 | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/pratibimb-marathi-natya-utsav-a-mix-of-commercial-and-experimental-plays/story-U4aGM5aNQhQvt5FxqRJR3L.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n''Kosala'' has been translated into eight Indian languages and also into English. The available translations of the novel are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Title !! Languge !! Translator !! Year !! Publisher !! Ref.\n|-\n| ''Cocoon'' || English  || Sudhakar Marathe || 1997 || Macmillan Publishers India, Chennai ||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KyHhAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|page=31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Hindi]] || - || 1983 || [[National Book Trust]], [[New Delhi]] ||\n|-\n| ''Kosheto'' || [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] || Usha Sheth || 1995  || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Kannada]] || Vaman Dattatraya Bendre || 1995 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||<ref name=\"Dutt1999\">{{cite book|author=Kartik Chandra Dutt|title=Who's who of Indian Writers, 1999: A-M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QA1V7sICaIwC&pg=PA127|year=1999|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-0873-5|page=127}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Palur Vah'' || [[Assamese language|Assamese]] || - || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] || Ajit Singh || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Need'' || [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || Vandana Alase Hazra || 2001 || [[Sahitya Akademi]], [[New Delhi]] ||<ref name=\"Rao2004\">{{cite book|last=Rao|first=D. S.|title=Five Decades: The National Academy of Letters, India : a Short History of Sahitya Akademi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JDsBBDoMccC&pg=PA11|year=2004|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-2060-7|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Urdu]] || - || 2002 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Koshapok'' || [[Odia language|Odia]] || - || 2005 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Google books|id=ywj6VehHd5oC}} (Marathi)\n* {{Google books|id=ue41AAAAMAAJ}} (Hindi translation)\n\n[[Category:1963 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n[[Category:Marathi novels]]\n[[Category:Existentialist novels]]\n[[Category:1963 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:1963 debut novels]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographical novels]]\n", "name_user": "FiveFaintFootprints", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublication:ce - removed comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosala_(novel)"}
